{"attack":true,"case":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1). The regime condition merges two independent requirements into a single threshold that is not stated as a measurable, pre-registerable quantity. The precision condition is given as R·(1 - SC_majority_margin) > (1-P)·SC_majority_rate, but SC_majority_margin and SC_majority_rate are not defined as functions of the named measurable quantities (e, k, P, R). The worked example fixes k=7, e≈0.25, SC accuracy≈0.71 to derive P > ~0.43, yet for k=7 and e=0.25 the SC majority margin is a deterministic function of e and k (it is 5/7 vs 2/7, margin = 3/7), so SC accuracy is ~0.92, not ~0.71; the ~0.71 figure corresponds to e=3/7 (margin 4/7 vs 3/7), a different point. The threshold P > ~0.43 is therefore computed from an inconsistent mix of parameters and cannot be reproduced as a pre-registered function of (e, k, P, R). The mechanism formula compounds this: net benefit = R·P_false_majority·N_false - FPR·P_true_majority·N_true introduces FPR, P_false_majority, P_true_majority, N_false, N_true — none mapped to the named measurables, and FPR is not derivable from P alone without the base error rate and the candidate-pool composition. The proposal thus names a condition ('critic precision > base error rate' in scope; 'P > ~0.43' in claim) without a single coherent measurable expression relating it to e, k, P, R, violating the requirement that the divergence condition be stated in measurable quantities rather than as an aspiration or an internally inconsistent bound.","counterexample":[{"k":7,"e":0.25,"expected_SC_accuracy":"~0.92 (margin 5/7 vs 2/7)","claim_states_SC_accuracy":"~0.71","derived_P_threshold":"> 0.43","issue":"threshold derived from wrong SC accuracy for the stated (k,e)"}]}